<p>We can quickly extract the even/odd parts by separating the function's T=
aylor series into even/odd exponents:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/06b5d911a5e484010306cfa9f60649da.png" width=3D"255" height=3D"78=
" alt=3D"
\begin{align*}
f(x) &amp;=3D f_\text{even}(x) + f_\text{odd}(x) \\
f_\text{even}(x) &amp;=3D c_0 + c_2 x^2 + c_4x^4 + \cdots \\
f_\text{odd}(x) &amp;=3D c_1 x + c_3x^3 + c_5x^5 \cdots
\end{align*}
" class=3D"tex"></p>

<h3><span id=3D"Even_and_Odd_Exponentials">Even and Odd Exponentials</span>=
</h3>

<p>Ok, we have our trick. Why not try to split up the famous exponential fu=
nction?</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/57c4683189f9e74ddebed533a6931e7b.png" width=3D"341" height=3D"11=
1" alt=3D"
\begin{align*}
e^x_{\text{even}} &amp;=3D \text{avg}[e^x, e^{-x}] =3D \frac{e^x + e^{-x}}{=
2} =3D \cosh(x) \\
e^x_\text{odd} &amp;=3D \text{avg}[e^x, -e^{-x}] =3D \frac{e^x - e^{-x}}{2}=
 =3D \sinh(x) \\
e^x &amp;=3D e^x_{\text{even}}  + e^x_{\text{odd}} =3D \cosh(x) + \sinh(x)
\end{align*}
" class=3D"tex"></p>

