<h3><span id=3D"Hyperbolic_Geometry">Hyperbolic Geometry</span></h3>

<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.quantamagazine.org/what-is-the-geometry-of-th=
e-universe-20200316/">shape of the universe</a> may be a hyperbola, and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_geometry">hyperbolic geome=
try</a> is used in special relativity (beyond my pay grade). If we do live =
in a giant hyperbola, I, uh, may be forced to recant my "exponentials first=
" stance.</p>

<h2><span id=3D"Summary">Summary</span></h2>

<p>The hyperbolic functions can be seen as exponential functions (relating =
time and growth) or geometric functions (relating area and coordinates). Hy=
perbolas, generally speaking, have logarithmic area and exponential coordin=
ates.</p>

