essage " data-role=3D"message" dir=3D"auto"><div><p>Still working through t=
he article but I wanted to share one perspective that doesn't seem to be me=
ntioned in the article. Euler's formula says that e^{ix}=3Dcos(x)+isin(x), =
but if you take i to be an "imaginary" square root of +1 (one that isn't  =
=C2=B11) then you get the formula e^{ix}=3Dcosh(x)+isinh(x). This traces ou=
t a hyperbola because you are always accelerating  (or growing) in the dire=
ction of your current position. When i^2=3D-1 you are always accelerating i=
nward, creating an orbit like there's gravity, but when i^2=3D+1,  you are =
always accelerating outward, and the curve you get is like an orbit in anti=
-gravity.</p></div></div><span class=3D"post-media"><ul data-role=3D"post-m=
